04918nam a22007815i 9780823238811DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232388117 a10.1515/97808232388112doi  a(DE-B1597)555293  a(OCoLC)647876440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB945.R64bT86 2009eb 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a1912221 aTunstall, Dwayne A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYes, But Not Quite :bEncountering Josiah Royce's Ethico-Religious Insight /cDwayne A. Tunstall. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Encountering Josiah Royce’s Ethico-Religious Insight -- tPart I. Josiah Royce’s Personalism -- t1. The ‘‘Conception of God’’ Debate: Setting the Stage for Royce’s Personalism -- t2. Haunted by Howison’s Criticism: The Birth of Royce’s Late Philosophy -- t3. Royce’s Late Philosophy -- t4. Royce’s Personalism -- tPart II. Extending Royce’s Ethico- Religious Insight: Royce on the Beloved Community, Agape , and Human Temporality -- t5. Royce’s Ethico-Religious Insight: A Hypothetical Postulate? -- t6. King’s Beloved Community, Royce’s Metaphysics -- t7. Coupling Royce’s Temporalism with Levinasian Insights -- tClosing Remarks -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book contends that Josiah Royce bequeathed to philosophy a novel idealism based on an ethico-religious insight. This insight became the basis for an idealistic personalism, wherein the Real is the personal and a metaphysics of community is the most appropriate approach to metaphysics for personal beings, especially in an often impersonal and technological intellectual climate. The first part of the book traces how Royce constructed his idealistic personalism in response to criticisms made by George Holmes Howison. That personalism is interpreted as an ethical and panentheistic one, somewhat akin to Charles Hartshorne's process philosophy. The second part investigates Royce's idealistic metaphysics in general and his ethico-religious insight in particular. In the course of these investigations, the author examines how Royce's ethico-religious insight could be strengthened by incorporating the philosophical theology of Dr. Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr., and Emmanuel Levinas's ethical metaphysics. The author concludes by briefly exploring the possibility that Royce's progressive racial anti-essentialism is, in fact, a form of cultural, antiblack racism and asks whether his cultural, antiblack racism taints his ethico-religious insight.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aEthics. 0aIdealism. 0aMetaphysics. 0aPersonalism. 0aReligion. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aReligion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082323054940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823238811?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823238811423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823238811/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL